[[File:An Object Lesson by Boston Public Library.jpg|thumb|An Object Lesson by Boston Public Library]]
{{distinguish|Object Lessons (novel)}}
An '''object lesson''' is a [[teaching method]] that consists of using a physical object or [[visual aid]] as a discussion piece for a lesson.
{{Wiktionary}}
==Description==

The object lesson approach is promoted in the educational philosophy of [[Johann Heinrich Pestalozzi]], who held that teaching should begin with observation of objects which help students recognize concepts.<ref>[http://www.lessonstudygroup.net/lg/readings/TheOriginofLessonStudyinJapanMakinaeN/TheOriginofLessonStudyinJapanMakinaeN.pdf MAKINAE, Naomichi. 2010. "The Origin of Lesson Study in Japan." Paper presented at EARCOME5, Japan Society of Mathematical Education]</ref>

==History==

Object lessons were important elements in teaching during the [[Victorian era]] of the mid- to late-nineteenth century.<ref>[http://hpsmuseumleeds.wordpress.com/2012/12/05/object-lessons/ "Object lessons" HPS Museum Blog (at the University of Leeds), 5 December 2012] ''(accessed 16 March 2013)''</ref> They are commonly used in [[religious instruction]].

